22:12.515 --> 22:19.606
And he had a separate, I can't remember what's in the catalog and what's not in the catalog.

22:19.626 --> 22:30.764
But he had a new style of, a new deal that he settled off with his publisher.

22:32.707 --> 22:40.699
And the deal was that he would

22:41.557 --> 23:01.996
He would pay all the expenses of having it done, but he would get all the profits, and the Chapman and Hall publishers would get a fixed commission on the number of copies sold.

23:04.058 --> 23:09.623
Well, the result of that was a disaster, which we'll predict as we'll come to a little bit later.

23:10.615 --> 23:25.212
But in trying to come out with a perfect book that he could still sell for very inexpensively, for five shillings, he experimented all over the place.

23:25.792 --> 23:27.494
Dickens did personally, right?

23:27.514 --> 23:27.635
Yeah.

23:28.696 --> 23:38.547
And the first thing he wanted to do, he wanted to have green endpapers, and he wanted to have

23:40.163 --> 23:46.070
a green and red title page.

23:48.513 --> 23:49.394
